# TestBase (Sync) Test Structure

Apply when writing or refactoring unit tests for code that has **no async methods** (mappers, managers, factories, etc.). These inherit from `TestBase<TSubject>` and use a **synchronous** lifecycle: configure mocks and data in the **constructor**, then call `BuildSubject()` and optionally `PostSetup()`.

## When to Use TestBase vs UseCaseTestBase

- **TestBase&lt;TSubject&gt;** – Subject under test has no async API. No `IAsyncLifetime`; configure mocks and data in the constructor, then call `BuildSubject()` and `PostSetup()`.
- **UseCaseTestBase&lt;TSubject&gt;** – Subject has async methods (e.g. `Execute`). Uses `InitializeAsync` / `DisposeAsync`; configure mocks and test data in the constructor (runs before `InitializeAsync`).

## Class and Namespace

- **Test class**: `{Name}Tests` inheriting from `TestBase<{SubjectType}>` (e.g. `{Entity}MapperTests : TestBase<{Entity}Mapper>`).
- **Namespace**: Mirror production (e.g. `LifeInsuranceCRM.Core.Tests.Mappers`, `LifeInsuranceCRM.Core.Tests.Managers`).
- **Top of class**: One property per mocked dependency using `MockFor<T>()` (e.g. `private Mock<INowProvider> NowProvider => MockFor<INowProvider>();`). Omit if the subject has no dependencies.

## Constructor and Lifecycle

- **Constructor**: Configure mocks and test data (if any), then call `BuildSubject(); PostSetup();` so the subject and any one-time results are ready before tests run.
- **BuildSubject()**: Builds the subject from mocks/dependencies. The constructor calls it after any mock/data setup.
- **PostSetup()**: Override to run **once after** the subject is built (e.g. call the mapper once and store the result in a field for property-based `[Fact]` methods). Optional if tests call the subject directly in each test.

## Nested Classes (Same as Use Case Tests)

- Use **nested classes** to group related facts (e.g. `Create`, `Update`, `DbToOutput` for mappers; `Generate` for a generator).
- Nested class inherits from the outer test class (e.g. `public class Create : {Entity}MapperTests`).
- When a nested class overrides `PostSetup()`, only that nested class's tests get that setup (virtual dispatch from base constructor).

## Inputs and Default Returns

- **Input variables**: Define as **fields** or **static readonly** at class level. Set in the constructor or use constants.
- **Default return values**: Class-level fields used in `Setup(...)` and in assertions. Use **Fixture** for anonymous data where “any value” is enough.
- **Exception objects**: Class-level fields (e.g. `_expectedException`), set in the constructor or in the test, used in `Setup(...).Throws(_expectedException)` and `Assert.Throws<...>(() => ...); Assert.Same(_expectedException, ex);`.

## Setups – Only What the Scenario Uses

- For each test (or nested class), **only Setup the calls that actually occur** in that scenario.
- Prefer **per-test or per-nested-class Setups**; keep the constructor to shared test data and default return-value fields, not broad mock behavior.

## Prefer Concrete Values in Setups and Verifies

- Use **actual input/field values** in `Setup(...)` and `Verify(...)` instead of `It.IsAny` when you have that value.
- Use **It.IsAny** when asserting a method was **never** called: `Verify(..., Times.Never)`.

## Mapper-Style Tests (One Call, Many Property Assertions)

- In **PostSetup()**: Call the subject once (e.g. `_createResult = SubjectUnderTest.Create(...);`) and store the result in a field.
- **`[Fact]` methods**: Assert one or a few properties each (e.g. `Name_IsMapped() => Assert.Equal("Alice", _createResult.Name);`).
- Keeps tests small and names document the mapped field.

## Conventions

- **SubjectUnderTest**: Use for the instance under test; built by `BuildSubject()` (or on first access if not using constructor flow).
- **Single logical assertion**: Prefer one logical assertion per test method.
- **Exception tests**: Use `Assert.Throws<T>(() => SubjectUnderTest.SomeMethod(...))` and, if relevant, assert the same exception instance.
- **No async**: Do not use `async`/`await` or `Task` in test methods or setup for TestBase-derived classes; use the sync overloads of the subject and mocks.
